node.text: Idaho 7® is the featured hop in Surly’s first in-person beer collaboration in well over a year. Our friends at Yakima Chief Hops and Jackson Hop Farm traveled from the Pacific Northwest to Minneapolis in June to work on an Idaho 7®-driven IPA that we’ll be piloting in our beer hall this summer in anticipation of a future package release. To learn more about this project, please enjoy this conversation between Nate, Ben, and Steve and Joe from YCH about this collaboration, what YCH does, and why they brought this hop to Surly.

node.title: The Future of Flavor: A Surly/YCH Collaboration

node.text: All that we know, all that we've ever known, and all we will know exist at the same time. Space, time, matter, energy, folding a fitted sheet, everything. Join Surly's Bob Galligan as he explores Mapping The Multiverse Hazy IPA, Surly's newest year-round beer.

node.text:
The traditional 14th anniversary gift is ivory. Two things about ivory you should know is that it’s remarkably cruel to animals and impossible to drink. Barleywines, on the other hand, are perfect for sipping and do zero harm to elephants.

Fourteen, Surly’s 14th anniversary beer, is just such a beer.

Surly's Ben Smith and Bob Galligan tell you all about it, give it a taste, and let you know what to expect from this massive barleywine.

node.text:
Introducing the 2021 Set List!

Every playlist or mixtape worth a damn sets the tone with an undeniable opener. Needless to say, Furious IPA is this Set List’s Side 1, Track 1. The rest of the show is all killer, no filler:

Fuzz Box. Named after the device that gave the world “Satisfaction” and inspired 100,000 garage bands, Fuzz Box spikes a tart ale base with passion fruit, orange, and guava, sending the beer into tropical overdrive.

Sonic Distortion. Dry-hopped on Citra and Mosaic, this bright, citrusy ale delivers an encore-worthy burst of hops at a lower ABV.

Sabrotooth Tiger. Speaking of encores, our most popular seasonal of 2020 returns to the stage. This IPA centers the ferocious Sabro hop and its formidably fruit-forward bite.

Link in bio for more info on the beers and our #turnitup promotion, where you can win four tickets to any 2022 Festival Field show.

Say what you will about Jason Voorhees, he was way ahead of the curve on wearing a mask and understood the importance of a good sequel.

Today (Friday, August 13th), Surly releases the 2021 batch of 13, our maple barrel-aged imperial stout brewed with vanilla beans and lactose. Expect notes of dark chocolate, roasted malt, and aromatic vanilla atop the rich maple flavors coursing beneath this luscious, decadent ale. Released for the first time on December 13th, 2019, this is your annual opportunity to partake in a truly exceptional beer experience.

Once again, this limited-run beer can be found in package as an individual 16 oz. can in an impossibly cool foil-embossed box designed by our remarkable creative team and executed with a vengeance by St. Paul’s @studioonfire. You can also find it on draft in our Beer Hall and select bars and restaurants.

Good luck out there.

All the things you need to know about attending tomorrow’s Patti Smith and Her Band show at Festival Field can be found at the link in bio. Three highlights:

*We strongly encourage biking, rideshares, and public transportation. Parking is limited, as noted by the accompanying map.

*If it’s your first Festival Field show, reminder that chairs are not allowed. Feel free to bring a blanket if you want to take a seat on our remarkably dead grass.

*It’s an outdoor show, so masks are not required. HOWEVER, feel free to wear one. We have plenty of room, but there can be lines for beer, food, and the restrooms. If you have a problem with someone wearing a mask, please find literally anything else to worry about.

It’s our first Festival Field show in two very long years. We’re beyond grateful to have live music back and we look forward to seeing all of you here.

node.text:
Slowly but surely, live music is returning. Beloved venues like Minneapolis’ First Avenue are finally reopening. The daily influx of new concert announcements, from stadium shows to nightclub gigs, are a welcome change of pace from Zoom concerts. If you’ve also found yourself giving a standing ovation to the busker playing atrocious Dave Matthews covers outside the Chipotle, you understand.

Surly’s Festival Field also comes back online this month with shows from Patti Smith (August 7) and Ween (August 21). To celebrate this and our new surly Set List variety pack, we’re giving away four tickets to any of our 2022 summer concerts. No, they haven’t been announced yet. But you’re going to want to have tickets when they are. 

To win: Post a shot of a great live show you attended on Facebook, Instagram, or Twitter. Tag @surlybrewing. Use the hashtag #turnitup. That's it. Contest ends on September 15th. Link in bio for more info on the contest and the beers!

node.text:
We’ve had a long, hot summer here. Chances are you have too. We’re also aware, more than most, that this summer will eventually end. We know what awaits. Making the most of the sunstruck days and warm evenings that remain on the calendar is essential. So is Invisible Rays.

Surly’s late-summer seasonal is a tropical IPA brimming with pineapple and guava notes from the Talus and Lotus hops. A kiss of lactose smooths out the finish of a beer radiant with fruit-forward flavor. Summer isn’t endless here, but you’ll wish this beer was.

Invisible Rays is available to all Surly markets beginning this week.
